  WHY: reformat_prompt.md's YAML example got silently mangled when edited through a markdown-aware tool; new version uses explicit section markers ('## End of required shape') and negative-example block so intent survives future edits
  CONTEXT: core/cluster/below/reformat_prompt.md
  WHY: Architecturally the worker is a filesystem poller that calls Ollama (http) and SSHs to Jimmy; nothing listens on Below. Future diagnostics must not assume HTTP
  CONTEXT: com.buildrunner.below-worker.plist, research_worker.py ResearchWorker.run
  WHY: User instruction; prior session demonstrated that silent-failure paths (bad prompt, stale remote, unclear skill docs) compound into "looks fine, nothing indexed"
  CONTEXT: 13/13 below cluster tests pass, launchd worker bounced to PID 49730, Jimmy reindex done (6812 chunks)
  WHY: BR3 runtime posture routes by command name, not action type. /root is Claude-pinned; follow-on "fix this" inherits the skill's model. No rule says "all build work → Codex"
  CONTEXT: ~/.buildrunner/ project_config, session-start brief, roy-concise profile
  WHY: Developer brief is injected as context strings. Tool calls fire based on model judgment, not config. Only hooks are a hard enforcement layer in Claude Code.
  CONTEXT: project_config resolved default, SessionStart hook
  WHY: Edit/Write alone leaves Bash holes (sed -i, >, >>, rm, mv, git apply). Classifier distinguishes read-ish vs write-ish Bash. Marker file tells hook when Codex work is sanctioned.
  CONTEXT: settings.json hooks, future wiring via /update-config
  WHY: Canonical Anthropic multi-agent pattern (lead decomposes → worker executes → lead reviews) maps directly to role-matrix intent. Closes the drift with one named entry point.
  CONTEXT: ~/.claude/skills/fixit/SKILL.md, .buildrunner/fixit-briefs/, .buildrunner/codex-allowed.flag
  WHY: Reflexion research shows gains concentrate in the first reflection; 2+ rounds cause oscillation not improvement. Explicit cap prevents infinite-loop failure modes.
  CONTEXT: /fixit Step 5 arbitration
  WHY: Codex gets a self-contained brief, not the main conversation. Prevents context pollution and makes the audit trail explicit. Matches existing /2nd convention.
  CONTEXT: Step 2 of /fixit, existing /2nd codex-briefs pattern
  WHY: Main branch is never the workspace. Worktree gives clean diff for review and prevents Codex from corrupting base state on abort. Diff is the unit of arbitration.
  CONTEXT: .worktrees/fixit-<ts>/, git worktree add in Step 3
  WHY: Future enforcement hook trusts the marker to allow Edit/Write under /fixit. Clearing on every exit path (success/abort/error) is the invariant the hook depends on.
  CONTEXT: Step 4 set, Step 7 clear, future PreToolUse hook
  WHY: Out-of-scope requests get named alternatives (/spec, /codex-do, /root, /review) rather than stretching /fixit. Scope creep is the usual failure mode for delegated-fix skills.
  CONTEXT: When-to-Use and Step 1 scope gate
  WHY: Separation of concerns. If Claude writes code under /fixit, the role matrix is defeated. Any Edit/Write call on source code inside the skill is a bug.
  CONTEXT: Rule 1 of /fixit
  WHY: Subjective "looks good" review fails silently. Deterministic gate catches regressions that look fine in a diff.
  CONTEXT: Step 6 verification
  WHY: If Claude picks up where Codex failed, the role matrix is defeated by the first hard problem. Abort with worktree preserved for human inspection.
  CONTEXT: Step 4 timeout, Step 7 abort
  WHY: Reflexion research — diminishing returns, oscillation. Cap at one revision; second failure → human.
  CONTEXT: Step 5 arbitration
  WHY: /fixit is ad-hoc, single-scope. Parallelism belongs to /autopilot. Keeps /fixit's failure mode trivial to reason about.
  CONTEXT: /fixit vs /autopilot boundary
  WHY: Orchestrator-worker pattern requires separation. Codex executes, Claude judges. Self-grading collapses the check.
  CONTEXT: Step 5 uses auto-review-diff.sh (Claude-side), not Codex self-report
  WHY: Explicit invocation first, measure scope-gate reliability for ~1 week, then consider auto-invoke. Premature auto-invoke removes the human gate before trust is established.
  CONTEXT: hook + /fixit integration, open question for next iteration
  WHY: classify-prompt.sh (scope gate), codex-bridge.sh (optional cluster context), auto-review-diff.sh (JSON-output review pipeline), decisions.log (audit). Reuse preserves invariants across skills.
  CONTEXT: ~/.buildrunner/scripts/, Steps 1/4/5/7 of /fixit
  WHY: Current state lets "fix this" silently land on Claude. Goal is deterministic routing via named skill + hook backstop, not probabilistic self-policing.
